1. Sign in to AWS

Open the AWS Management Console and sign in using your company IAM/SSO account.

Do not use the AWS root account for this project.

2. Select the AWS Region

At the top-right corner of the AWS Console, select the Region provided by the hackathon team.

When no Region was provided, use:

US East (N. Virginia)
us-east-1

We will create all OpsAI resources in the same Region. Bedrock model availability can differ between Regions.

3. Open AWS CloudShell

At the top of the AWS Console, click the CloudShell icon:

>_

CloudShell already contains AWS CLI version 2 and automatically uses your AWS Console permissions. You do not need to create or enter AWS access keys.

4. Run These Commands

Copy and run this complete block in CloudShell:

# Set our project Region
export AWS_REGION=us-east-1
export AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1

# Check AWS CLI
aws --version

# Check which AWS account and role you are using
aws sts get-caller-identity

# Confirm the selected Region
echo "AWS Region: $AWS_REGION"

# Check Amazon Bedrock access
aws bedrock list-foundation-models \
  --region "$AWS_REGION" \
  --query 'modelSummaries[0:5].[modelName,providerName]' \
  --output table

# Check S3 access
aws s3api list-buckets \
  --query 'Buckets[0:5].Name' \
  --output table

# Check Lambda access
aws lambda list-functions \
  --region "$AWS_REGION" \
  --max-items 5 \
  --query 'Functions[].FunctionName' \
  --output table

# Check CloudWatch Logs access
aws logs describe-log-groups \
  --region "$AWS_REGION" \
  --limit 5 \
  --query 'logGroups[].logGroupName' \
  --output table

# Check Bedrock Knowledge Base access
aws bedrock-agent list-knowledge-bases \
  --region "$AWS_REGION" \
  --max-results 5 \
  --query 'knowledgeBaseSummaries[].name' \
  --output table

The aws sts get-caller-identity command shows the AWS user or role currently being used.

Expected Result

It is okay when some tables are empty because we have not created resources yet.

The important result is:
No AccessDenied errors



